definition.value: An acetal of formula R2C(OR)2 (R =/= H) derived from a ketone by replacement of the oxo group by two hydrocarbyloxy groups. The class name 'ketals', once abandoned by IUPAC, has been reinstated as a subclass of acetals.
A ketal in the molecule of which the ketal carbon and one or both oxygen atoms thereon are members of a ring.

A hemiacetal  having the structure R2C(OH)OR (R =/= H), derived from a ketone by formal addition of an alcohol to the carbonyl group. The term 'cyclic hemiketals', once abandoned by IUPAC, has been reinstated as a subclass of hemiacetals.
The 3',5'-di-O-methyl ether of tricetin.  Known commonly as tricin, it is a constituent of rice bran and has been found to potently inhibit colon cancer cell growth.
A chemical substance is a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types.
A mixture is a chemical substance composed of multiple molecules, at least two of which are of a different kind.
A polymer is a mixture, which is composed of macromolecules of different kinds and which may be differentiated by composition, length, degree of branching etc..

An acylglycerophosphocholine resulting from partial hydrolysis of a phosphatidylcholine, which removes one of the fatty acyl groups. The structure is depicted in the image where R1 = acyl, R2 = H or where R1 = H, R2 = acyl.
A monomethoxyflavone that is quercetin in which the hydroxy group at position 3' is replaced by a methoxy group.
The selenium ion with two positive charges.
Any  amino sugar that is a monosaccharide in which one alcoholic hydroxy group is replaced by an amino group.
A glucoside in which the anomeric carbon of the glycosidic bond is in an alpha configuration
A monomethoxyflavone that is the 4'-O-methyl derivative of kaempferol.
Any compound that has a nucleobase as a part.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having five C=C double bonds.

Hemicelluloses are polysaccharides in plant cell walls that have beta-(1->4)-linked backbones with an equatorial configuration. Hemicelluloses include xyloglucans, xylans, mannans and glucomannans, and beta-(1->3,1->4)-glucans.
A polymer, composed of polysiloxane macromolecules.
A polysiloxane polymer, composed of silicone macromolecules.
A silicone polymer, composed of polydimethylsiloxane macromolecules.
A polydimethylsiloxane polymer, composed of dimethicone macromolecules.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): anticaking agent, antifoaming agent, emulsifier.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a fatty acid.

A carbobicyclic compound and sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,7-octahydronaphthalene which is substituted a prop-1-en-2-yl group at position 3 and by methyl groups at positions 4a and 5  (the 3R,4aS,5R- diastereoisomer).
The five-membered ring form of L-arabinose.
A lipid-rich mixture containing glycerol, fatty acids, phosphoric acid and other components.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of one or more oxoacid OH groups of any polysaccharide acid.
An acyclic psi,psi-carotene having cis double bonds at C-7, -7', -9 and -9'.
An ester where the ester linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.

An inorganic sulfate salt obtained by reaction of sulfuric acid with two equivalents of ammonia. A high-melting (decomposes above 280degreeC) white solid which is very soluble in water (70.6 g/100 g water at 0degreeC; 103.8 g/100 g water at 100degreeC), it is widely used as a fertilizer for alkaline soils.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flour treatment agent, stabilizer.
An organic sodium salt which is the monosodium salt of formic acid.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan (cellulose) in amorphous form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by beta(1->4) glycosidic linkages.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan (cellulose) in crystalline form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by beta(1->4) glycosidic linkages.
An acetate salt in which the cationic component is zinc(2+).
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flavour enhancer.
The inorganic nitrate salt of sodium.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour fixative, preservative.
The organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of L-tartaric acid.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, sequestrant, stabilizer.
The potassium salt of L-tartaric acid.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, sequestrant, stabilizer.
The organic sodium and potassium salt of L-tartaric acid (mol ratio 1:1:1).
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, sequestrant, stabilizer.
A potassium salt in which dihydrogen phosphate(1-) is the counterion.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, buffer, emulsifier, humectant, moisture-retention agent, sequestrant, stabilizer, texturizing agent.
A citrate salt in which all three carboxy groups are deprotonated and associated with ammonium ions as counter-cations.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator.
The inorganic nitrate salt of potassium.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour fixative, preservative.
An organic cation resulting from protonation or quaternisation at the 3-position of any 1,3-thiazole.
A carbohydrate derivative arising formally from the elimination of water from a glycosidic hydroxy group and an H atom bound to an oxygen, carbon, nitrogen or sulfur atom of a separate entity.

Any organooxygen compound derived from a carbohydrate by replacement of one or more hydroxy group(s) by an amino group, a thiol group or similar heteroatomic groups. The term also includes derivatives of these compounds.
The potassium salt of formic acid.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from a disaccharide.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from a monosaccharide.
A monosaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a pentose.
A carboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of a carbohydrate acid derivative.
A tunaxanthin that consists of epsilon,epsilon-carotene bearing hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 3' (the 3S,3'S,6S,6'S-diastereomer).
